    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="# Starlink Satellite Useful Life & Depreciation Policies\n\nBased on the financial statement excerpts you've provided, here's a comprehensive summary:\n\n## Estimated Useful Life of Starlink Satellites\n\nThe company estimates satellite useful lives based on **engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, and planned transitions to newer satellite technology**:\n\n| Satellite Type | Estimated Useful Life |\n|---|---|\n| **Broadband satellites** | **5 years** |\n| **First-generation mobile satellites** | **3 years** |\n| **Overall range (from PP&E schedule)** | **3–5 years** |\n\nThe company also notes it **often deorbits satellites before the end of their useful lives**, primarily to reduce degradation risks that could impair their autonomous collision avoidance system.\n\n## Depreciation Method\n\nUnlike most PP&E assets (which use straight-line over calendar time), **flight vehicles and spacecraft are depreciated based on the expected number of average flights**. However, **satellites specifically are depreciated over their estimated useful lives** (3–5 years) using straight-line depreciation, factoring in:\n\n- On-orbit performance\n- Orbit-raise timing\n- Expected service capability\n- Evolution of constellation density and technology\n\n## How Depreciation Flows Through the Financials\n\n- **Launch costs** incurred to place Starlink satellites into orbit are **capitalized as part of the satellite asset** (included in PP&E), not expensed immediately.\n- Depreciation of these capitalized launch and satellite costs flows through **Cost of Revenue** in the Connectivity segment.\n- This was a **significant and growing cost driver**:\n  - **2025 vs 2024**: Higher depreciation of **$827 million** from capitalized launch and satellite costs\n  - **Q1 2026 vs Q1 2025**: Higher depreciation of **$276 million**\n  - **2024 vs 2023**: Higher depreciation of **$555 million**\n\n## Sensitivity to Useful Life Estimates\n\nThe disclosures note that **if the average useful life of satellite assets had been changed by one year**, the impact on operating income would have been approximately:\n\n- **$480 million** for the year ended December 31, 2025\n- **$170 million** for Q1 2026\n\nThis underscores how sensitive profitability is to the assumed satellite lifespan.\n\n## Revision of Estimates\n\nThe company states that when useful lives are determined to be **shorter or longer than originally estimated**, the depreciation rate is adjusted prospectively to reflect the revised useful life. Management periodically reviews these estimates with engineering and operations teams.\n\n## Impairment Considerations\n\n- For the years ended December 31, 2025 and 2024, the company recorded **$38 million** and **$63 million** in impairment charges, respectively, including damaged satellite hardware in the Connectivity segment.\n- Impairment is evaluated whenever events or circumstances indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable (e.g., technological developments, declining cash flows, negative trends).\n\n## Key Accounting Insight\n\nInter-segment Starlink launches **do not generate revenue** for the Space segment. Instead, those launch costs are simply **capitalized into the satellite asset** and then depreciated over the satellite's useful life. This means the true economic cost of the Starlink constellation is recognized gradually through depreciation in the Connectivity segment's cost of revenue rather than at the point of launch.",
